Michelin-Level Bang Bang Chicken
Crisp, light, non-greasy. Proper starch balance, controlled hydration, correct double-fry, restrained sauce.

⸻

Yield

4 servings

⸻

Component 1 — Chicken Prep (Moisture control)
	•	1 lb (450 g) boneless, skinless chicken breast or thigh
	•	1 large egg
	•	⅓ cup (80 ml) whole milk
	•	½ tsp fine salt

Method
	1.	Cut chicken into 2.5 cm (1-inch) cubes.
	2.	Whisk egg, milk, salt. Add chicken, toss to coat.
	3.	Rest 15 minutes.
	4.	Drain thoroughly in a sieve. Chicken should be tacky, not wet.

Purpose: surface protein adhesion, not batter.

⸻

Component 2 — Dry Coating (Crisp shell, not breading)
	•	¼ cup (30 g) potato starch
	•	¼ cup (30 g) all-purpose flour
	•	½ tsp fine salt
	•	¼ tsp freshly ground black pepper
	•	¼ tsp shichimi togarashi (optional, correct)

Method
	1.	Combine all dry ingredients evenly.
	2.	Add chicken and toss until just coated.
	3.	Shake off excess. No clumping.

Ratio note:
50/50 starch/flour is deliberate — starch for shatter, flour for structure.

⸻

Component 3 — Frying (Double-stage, mandatory)
	•	Neutral oil (canola or peanut), 5–6 cm / 2 inches deep

Fry 1 — Cook-through
	•	Oil: 165 °C / 325 °F
	•	Time: 90 seconds

Cook in small batches. Remove to rack (not paper).

Fry 2 — Crisp
	•	Oil: 175 °C / 350 °F
	•	Time: 90 seconds

Return chicken, fry until pale golden and audibly crisp. Drain on rack.

Result: dry, rigid crust that accepts sauce without sogging.

⸻

Component 4 — Bang Bang Sauce (Balanced, not sweet)
	•	¼ cup (60 ml) Japanese mayonnaise
	•	1½ tbsp honey
	•	1½ tbsp sweet chili sauce
	•	1 tsp gochujang
	•	1 tsp rice vinegar or fresh lime juice
	•	Pinch fine salt

Method
Whisk until smooth. Taste should be:
	•	sweet → immediate
	•	heat → delayed
	•	acid → clean finish

No garlic. No sesame oil. Correct restraint.

⸻

Final Assembly
	1.	Toss chicken lightly with sauce — coat, don’t drown.
	2.	Finish with:
	•	thinly sliced scallions
	•	optional red chili

Serve immediately.

⸻

Chef Standards (Why this is “perfect”)
	•	Milk-egg marinade hydrates without battering
	•	Drained protein prevents gumminess
	•	Correct starch ratio for crispness
	•	Double-fry temperatures are precise
	•	Sauce balanced for fried food, not wings

